<paragraph id="A7CEE4714AE1B5F328F6D05041472CD0" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="18308EC8B5B7C66C4AE62194DCDF1189" LSID="57276AA3-EFAB-59D2-AAEA-2249F508A66E" authority="Thorell, 1891" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1891" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Pharta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pharta" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pharta Thorell, 1891</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="25800D31C067CC37930C4C879043ACEA" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="comments">
<paragraph id="E9FC7106736FCE384519819D30A9908C" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F533959582A7C77566C7D52567E442A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
This genus includes nine species, the majority of which are distributed in Southeast Asia (
<bibRefCitation id="5612EF3CD4CCCA975C8043EFE6D4C7BB" author="World Spider Catalog" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" publicationUrl="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" refId="B24" refString="World Spider Catalog, 2022. World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5. https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" title="World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5." url="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" year="2022">WSC 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Four species are known to occur in China, all in Yunnan and Guizhou provinces (
<bibRefCitation id="BD8EE234CAF5EE5736549803E6FE8277" author="Li, SQ" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" refId="B7" refString="Li, SQ, Lin, YC, 2016. Species Catalogue of China. Vol. 2. Animals. Invertebrates (1). Arachnida: Araneae. Science Press, Beijing" title="Species Catalogue of China. Vol. 2. Animals. Invertebrates (1). Arachnida: Araneae." year="2016">Li and Lin 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Among them, only 
<taxonomicName id="47207B99B95CB8E2D4D789CA7878F483" genus="P." lsidName="P. tengchong" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="tengchong">
<emphasis id="F066F712C2F254E0B9186B3A3AC1B6ED" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">P. tengchong</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Tang, Griswold &amp; Yin, 2009) is known from the female.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
